  coaching_execution = '{"movement_description":"Single-Leg RDL Negative is a slow negative/eccentric drill for single-leg posterior-chain and pelvis control. It uses deliberate lowering, clean alignment, and enough rest to build control and tissue capacity without chasing fatigue.","setup":["Stand on one foot with light support available; use no load until balance is clean.","Choose a load, range, height, or lever length that allows a smooth negative without pain.","Set the athlete''s start position before adding tempo or volume."],"execution_steps":["Create tension and start from a position the athlete can own.","Reach the back leg long and hinge for 4-5 seconds; return only from the range the athlete can own.","Keep breathing controlled and avoid bouncing, dropping, twisting, or rushing the last third of the range.","Reset each rep so the next negative starts from the same clean position."],"coach_cues":["Slow is the load.","Own the last third.","Stop before compensation.","Quiet breath, quiet joints."],"athlete_cues":["Move like you could pause anywhere.","Control the down, reset the up.","No pain, no collapse."],"breathing_cues":["Inhale before the rep if needed, then exhale slowly through the lowering phase.","Do not use breath holding to hide loss of position."],"common_faults":["Rushing the negative after the first half of the range.","Adding load before the athlete owns tempo and alignment.","Turning a tissue-control drill into a fatigue circuit.","Pushing through pain, joint pinch, or visible collapse."],"quality_gate":["Tempo stays within the prescribed range.","Target joint line stays clean with no uncontrolled wobble or collapse.","Athlete finishes the set with the same posture and range they started with.","No pain response during the set or unusual next-day flare-up."],"stop_signs":["Sharp pain, cramping that changes mechanics, numbness, dizziness, or joint pinch.","Tempo cannot be maintained for the planned range.","Breath holding, shaking, or compensation becomes the main strategy."]}'::jsonb,
